FPP - Ch. 5 Exercises

Time Series Regression Models
Dan Hong | dnaeye@gmail.com

The following are my answers to the exercises in the excellent book Forecasting: Principles & Practice by Rob J Hyndman and George Athanasopoulos.

1. Create a regression model and forecasts for electricity demand in Victoria, Australia.

1a. Plot the data and find the regression model for Demand with temperature as an explanatory variable. Why is there a positive relationship?

library(fpp2)
Loading required package: ggplot2
Loading required package: forecast
Loading required package: fma
Loading required package: expsmooth
daily20 <- head(elecdaily,20)
autoplot(daily20, facets=TRUE)

daily20 %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Temperature, y=Demand)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method="lm", se=FALSE)

fit <- tslm(Demand ~ Temperature, data=daily20)

  When the temperature goes up, electricity demand goes up as well because of air conditioning needs.   1b. Produce a residual plot. Is the model adequate? Are there any outliers or influential observations?

checkresiduals(fit)

    Breusch-Godfrey test for serial correlation of
    order up to 5

data:  Residuals from Linear regression model
LM test = 3.8079, df = 5, p-value = 0.5774

Based on the high p-value from the Breusch-Godfrey test and the absence of lags with significant ACF, the model is adequate. The residuals plot indicates there were significant outliers where the actual demand was much lower than the expected demand.

fc <- forecast(fit, test)

1e. Plot Demand vs Temperature for all of the available data in elecdaily. What does this say about your model?

elecdaily %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  ggplot(aes(Temperature, Demand)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_line(data=fortify(fit), aes(x=Temperature, y=.fitted), color="blue")

  Whne plotting my original model, which was based on just the first 20 days of 2014, it’s obvious that it did not adequately explain patterns for the rest of the year. It failed to explain any temperature lower than 20 degrees, for which the data shows an upward trend in demand as temperatures decreased. A possible explanation for this could be that during colder weather, people tended to stay indoors and use electric heaters.

2. Data set mens400 contains the winning times (in seconds) for the men’s 400 meters final in each Olympic Games from 1896 to 2016.

2a. Plot the winning time against the year. Describe the main features of the plot.

autoplot(mens400)

  There is a general negative trend with a few gaps of data between 1910 and 1920 and again from 1935 to 1948 (all years approximate).

2b. Fit a regression line to the data. Obviously the winning times have been decreasing, but at what average rate per year?

mens400 %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=as.numeric(time(mens400)), y=as.numeric(mens400))) + 
  xlab("year") + ylab("time") +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method="lm", se=FALSE)

m400.fit <- tslm(mens400 ~ trend)

  The average rate per year is -0.2582954.

2c. Plot the residuals against the year. What does this indicate about the suitability of the fitted line?

checkresiduals(m400.fit)

    Breusch-Godfrey test for serial correlation of
    order up to 6

data:  Residuals from Linear regression model
LM test = 3.6082, df = 6, p-value = 0.7295

  The residuals time plot doesn’t exhibit any pattern, and the residuals distribution plot is fairly normal. However, there was significant ACF at lag 2.

2d. Predict the winning time for the men’s 400 meters final in the 2020 Olympics. Give a prediction interval for your forecasts. What assumptions have you made in these calculations?

forecast(m400.fit, h=1)
  Point Forecast Lo 80 Hi 80 Lo 95 Hi 95
1       42.04231    NA    NA    NA    NA

The forecast using time-series linear regression for the winning time in 2020 is 42.04.

Because the trend resembles a random walk, the rwf model would be appropriate to make a forecast with a prediction interval.

rwf(mens400, drift=T, h=1)

4. An elasticity coefficient is the ratio of the percentage change in the forecast variable \(y\) to the percentage change in the predictor variable \(x\).

Mathematically, the elasticity is defined as \((dy/dx) \times (x/y)\). Consider the log-log model, \[log~y = \beta_0 + \beta_1log~x + E\] Express \(y\) as a function of \(x\) and show that the coefficient \(\beta_1\) is the elasticity coefficient.

If you take the exponentials of both sides,

\[y = \epsilon^{\beta_0} + x^{\beta_1} + \epsilon^E\] I do not know how to show that the coefficient \(\beta_1\) is the elasticity coefficient.

5. The data set fancy concerns the monthly sales figures of a shop which opened in January 1987 and sells gifts, souvenirs, and novelties.

The shop is situated on the wharf at a beach resort town in Queensland, Australia. The sales volume varies with the seasonal population of tourists. There is a large influx of visitors to the town at Christmas and for the local surfing festival, held every March since 1988. Over time, the shop has expanded its premises, range of products, and staff.

5a. Produce a time plot of the data and describe the patterns in the graph. Identify any unusual or unexpected fluctuations in the time series.

autoplot(fancy)

 

As noted in the description of the dataset, there were seasonal spikes in December and a smaller one every March since 1988. There has also been an upward trend since 1991.

5b. Explain why it is necessary to take logarithms of these data before fitting a model.

The data should be log transformed because the seasonal variances are increasing.

5c. Use R to fit a regression model to the logarithms of these sales data with a linear trend, seasonal dummies and a “surfing festival” dummy variable.

dummy_fest = rep(0, length(fancy))
dummy_fest[seq_along(dummy_fest)%%12 == 3] <- 1
dummy_fest[3] <- 0 #festival started one year later
dummy_fest = ts(dummy_fest, freq = 12, start=c(1987,1))
fancy.fit <- tslm(fancy ~ trend + season + dummy_fest, lambda=0)
summary(fancy.fit)

The Breusch-Godfrey test returned a p-value lower than 0.05 indicating there is no significant autocorrelation remaining in the residuals, although the ACF plot shows some autocorrelation at lag 2 and at a few other lags.

The residuals vs. fitted plot shows a slight parabola in the middle range of fitted values, indicating that for this range of values, the model is predicting significantly higher than the actual observed values.

5e. Do boxplots of the residuals for each month. Does this reveal any problems with the model?

ggplot() + geom_boxplot(mapping=aes(x=month.factor, y=as.numeric(residuals(fancy.fit)))) + labs(x = "Months", y = "Residuals")

The boxplot of residuals reveals that the model produces a lot of variance in March and in the fall months, from August to October.

5f. What do the values of the coefficients tell you about each variable?

The log-transformed coefficients for each month tell us how large the sales are in relation to January’s sales. For example, the coefficient for December (i.e., season12) is about 1.96, but because the model has a lambda of 0, all fitted values have been log transformed. To get the true multiplier for December, you need to raise natural log to a power of 1.96: \(\epsilon^{1.96}\) = 7.0993271

5g. What does the Breusch-Godfrey test tell you about your model?

As mentioned above, the Breusch-Godfrey test returned a p-value lower than 0.05 indicating there is no significant autocorrelation remaining in the residuals.

6. The gasoline series consists of weekly data for supplies of US finished motor gasoline product, from 2 February 1991 to 20 January 2017. The units are in “million barrels per day”. Consider only the data to the end of 2004.

6a. Fit a harmonic regression with trend to the data. Experiment with changing the number Fourier terms. Plot the observed gasoline and fitted values and comment on what you see.

m = 52 weeks, so 26 Fourier terms

gas9104 <- window(gasoline, end=2005)
fourier.gas26 <- tslm(gas9104 ~ trend + fourier(gas9104, K=26))
autoplot(gas9104) + autolayer(fitted(fourier.gas26))

  ** m = 12 months, so 6 Fourier terms **

fourier.gas6 <- tslm(gas9104 ~ trend + fourier(gas9104, K=6))
autoplot(gas9104) + autolayer(fitted(fourier.gas6))

  ** m = 4 quarters, so 2 Fourier terms **

fourier.gas2 <- tslm(gas9104 ~ trend + fourier(gas9104, K=2))
autoplot(gas9104) + autolayer(fitted(fourier.gas2))

  The model fits the observed data better with more Fourier terms, as with K = 26, but this may lead to overfitting.

6c. Check the residuals of the final model using the checkresiduals() function.

Even though the residuals fail the correlation tests, the results are probably not severe enough to make much difference to the forecasts and prediction intervals. (Note that the correlations are relatively small, even though they are significant.)

checkresiduals(fourier.gas6)

    Breusch-Godfrey test for serial correlation of
    order up to 104

data:  Residuals from Linear regression model
LM test = 147.59, df = 104, p-value = 0.003212

As explained in the textbook, residuals testing indicates that the model exhibits some autocorrelation, as demonstrated by the low p-value in the Breusch-Godfrey test and the ACF plot which has multiple significant lags. However, the residuals distribution plot looks quite normal with only a slight tail to the right.

gas05 <- window(gasoline, start=2005, end=2006)

The fourier forecast roughly matches the general trend of the actual data for 2005, but there seems to be a dramatic drop in the actuals around August that wasn’t expected by the model.  

7. Data set huron gives the water level of Lake Huron in feet from 1875 to 1972.

7a. Plot the data and comment on its features.

autoplot(huron)

The plot shows a general negative trend. There are several shocks in 1925, 1935, 1957, and 1965, which might have been caused by drought.

  Although the piecewise model has higher point forecasts than the linear model, the prediction interval is tighter.

lr80 <- mean(fcasts.lr$upper[,1]-fcasts.lr$lower[,1])
pw80 <- mean(fcasts.pw$upper[,1]-fcasts.pw$lower[,1])
lr95 <- mean(fcasts.lr$upper[,2]-fcasts.lr$lower[,2])
pw95 <- mean(fcasts.pw$upper[,2]-fcasts.pw$lower[,2])

The average size of the 80% confidence interval for the linear model was 2.9835803 while that for the piecewise model was 2.7973958, which was -6.24% lower.

The average size of the 95% confidence interval for the linear model was 4.5894384 while that for the piecewise model was 4.3033077, which was -6.23% lower.
